h3. Issue Summary

As special characters are not stored in index, you are unable to perform searches if a JQL query includes a special character. Due to that, as an alternative, we use the custom field ID instead.

For example, we cannot search for custom field 'Client[s]' as it will return as Clients. So we amend it to look like this :
{code:java}
project = 'Jira' AND cf[10401] = Atlassian{code}
However, if using the JQL query above for a Two Dimensional Gadget, then, clicking on one of the results, it will instead show filter with special characters when clicking on the results with the error "Field: 'xxx' does not exist or you do not have permission to view it".
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a filter that includes the ID of a custom field that has a special character. For example, the custom field 'Client[s]'.

{code:java}
project = 'Jira' AND cf[10401] = Atlassian {code}

 # Save the filter as test.
 # Go to a dashboard. Add the 'Two Dimensional Filter'. Choose the filter 'test'. Add the field 'Client[s]' as an X-axis and Assignee as Y-axis.
 # Once the results is displayed, click on one of the results.

h3. Expected Results

Jira will redirect us to the filter :
{code:java}
project = Jira AND cf[10401] = Atlassian AND assignee is EMPTY {code}
h3. Actual Results

Jira will instead redirect to the filter with the following JQL Query.
{code:java}
project = tpm Jira AND cf[10401] = Atlassian AND Client[s] = "Atlassian" AND assignee is EMPTY {code}
The error  "Field: 'xxx' does not exist or you do not have permission to view it".will be seen.
h3. Workaround

Remove the custom field with special character in the JQL query

h3. Summary
When batched notifications feature is enabled, the email received will have the line 'Updates For' in the subject. For example : 
{code:java}
Test Jira Updates for TN-14 : Test batching email notifications {code}

As this can be quite tedious when viewing dozens of letters in the mail client, it is difficult to quickly find the mail notification that you need.

h3. Issue Summary
Using REST API to create issues it is possible to use archived Fix Versions 

h3. Steps to Reproduce
Follow the documentation from the REST API [Create Issue |https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/8.4.2/#api/2/issue] to create an issue using the endpoint: {code}<JIRA Base URL>/rest/api/2/issue{code}
For example: {code}{
  "fields": {
    "project": {
      "id": "10101"
    },
    "summary": "something's wrong 1",
    "issuetype": {
      "id": "10002"
    },
    "assignee": {
      "name": "rene"
    },
    "reporter": {
      "name": "rene"
    },
    "fixVersions": [
		{ "name": "1" }
	], 
    "description": "description"
  }
}{code}
* Version "1" should be an archived version in the project.

h3. Expected Results
The issue is not created, indicating that the version is archived or invalid.

h3. Actual Results
The issue gets created: !screenshot-1.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Workaround
In this case, there is no way to prevent the creation of issues, setting the Fix Versions using archived versions.

Renaming users in Jira more than once cause UI elements to display their {{user_key}} rather than username, this can be misleading.

Steps to reproduce:
# Create any user;
# Rename the user once;
#* Note that the {{lower_user_name}} will be used on the first rename;
# Rename the user a second time;
#* Note that the format will be shown as "{{user_key}} ({{username}});

Suggestion:
Always show username or {{lower_user_name}} before the {{user_key}}.

h3. Issue Summary
REST API for Remote Linked Issues does not return resolution

h3. Steps to Reproduce
Run the REST API {code}<Jira BASE URL>/rest/api/latest/issue/{issue-key}/remotelink{code}
* The issue should have an issue linked from a different Jira instance.

h3. Expected behavior
According to the documentation [Get remote issue links|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/8.4.2/?_ga=2.208206162.1731011008.1571054532-864360301.1551767553#api/2/issue-getRemoteIssueLinks] the REST API should return something like this:
{code}{
        "id": 10000,
        "self": "http://www.example.com/jira/rest/api/issue/MKY-1/remotelink/10000",
        "globalId": "system=http://www.mycompany.com/support&id=1",
        "application": {
            "type": "com.acme.tracker",
            "name": "My Acme Tracker"
        },
        "relationship": "causes",
        "object": {
            "url": "http://www.mycompany.com/support?id=1",
            "title": "TSTSUP-111",
            "summary": "Crazy customer support issue",
            "icon": {
                "url16x16": "http://www.mycompany.com/support/ticket.png",
                "title": "Support Ticket"
            },
            "status": {
                "resolved": true,
                "icon": {
                    "url16x16": "http://www.mycompany.com/support/resolved.png",
                    "title": "Case Closed",
                    "link": "http://www.mycompany.com/support?id=1&details=closed"
                }
            }
        }
    }{code}

h3. Actual results
We get the "status" element empty, missing the resolution along with other information:
{code}[ 
   { 
      "id":10000,
      "self":"http://localhost:8080/rest/api/latest/issue/SD2-1/remotelink/10000",
      "globalId":"appId=6a05913b-4c3a-3c65-a8bd-f550f9c6fa09&issueId=10208",
      "application":{ 
         "type":"com.atlassian.jira",
         "name":"Jira"
      },
      "relationship":"blocks",
      "object":{ 
         "url":"http://localhost:8089/browse/SS-1",
         "title":"SS-1",
         "icon":{ 

         },
         "status":{ 
            "icon":{ 

            }
         }
      }
   }
]{code}

h3. Workaround
Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

