h3. Issue Summary

Atlassian Logging 2.x is shipped with Jira 8.5 EAP. The class NewLineIndentingFilteringPatternLayout code eats up a stacktrace because of a simple count error.

It is *very* confusing when the error logs are missing the most crucial information without any indication. It cost us quite some time...

h3. Environment

h3. Steps to Reproduce

In a particular stack trace, we notice that there is no call to Preconditions.checkArgument inside DelegatingEntityPropertyService.setProperty().
I think the stacktrace is missing one frame (for whatever reason).

h3. Expected Results

The entire stack trace is printed.

h3. Actual Results

A line is missing from the stack trace thrown.
 
h3. Notes

I investigated some more into the issues with the missing stackframe in the log.
This issue seems to have been fixed somewhere in a 3.X release of the Atlassian Logging library which Jira also uses.
 Jira 8.5 (tested with 8.5.0-EAP02) will only ship a version 2.X of Atlassian Logging that contains this bug.

This is the fix, for completeness sake:

{noformat}
 public class StackTraceCompressor {
 
@@ -168,7 +160,7 @@
             {
                 // after a cause by line we reset and show the next min lines and then start filtering all over again
                 appendSkipIndicators(buffer, filteredCount, eludedLineSummary);
-                lineCount = outputMinimumLines(buffer, stackTraceLines, lineCount, getMinimumLines());
+                lineCount = outputMinimumLines(buffer, stackTraceLines, lineCount, getMinimumLines()) - 1;
                 ignoreLinesUntilEnd = false;
                 continue;
             }
{noformat}

h3. Workaround

We have another log appender that save the same log and there the frame is indeed present.

h3. Issue Summary

Linking Issues: Users without "Browse Projects" & "Link Issues" permissions in Project B but have these permissions in Project A, Users can the link issues from project B with issues in project A using a known issue key from project B.

h3. Environment

- Jira 7.13.5

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Let's say we have project "A" and project "B";
 # One group have the "Browse projects" and "Link Issues" permissions only in project "A", but not in project "B";
 # Users in that group will be able to see issues from project A but not from project B, the user obtained an issue key from project B (Ex. from a colleague);
 # If you link an issue from project A in an issue from project A, the user will be able to link and see the "linked issues" just fine;
 # If you try to link an issue in Project A;
 # With an issue from project B which you don't have the "Browse projects" and "Link Issues" permissions;
 # Using the issue key known, you still can link them, but you won’t be able to see the link;
 # Other users who have "Browse projects" permission for project B will be able to see the link you have made;

h3. Expected Results 
Users *shouldn’t be able to* Link issues from projects which they don’t have "Browse Projects" & "Link Issues" permissions in.

h3. Actual Results
Users *can* link issues from projects which they don’t have "Browse Projects" & "Link Issues" permissions in.

h3. Workaround
None.
